In .NET MAUI, those same three virtual methods still exist on `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Application`, so your overrides carry over directly:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override void OnStart() { /* same as before */ }
    protected override void OnSleep() { /* same as before */ }
    protected override void OnResume() { /* same as before */ }
}
```

**However**, MAUI also adds a more granular lifecycle via the `Window` class. You can override `CreateWindow` and hook into window-level events:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* window created */ };
    window.Activated += (s, e) => { /* brought to foreground */ };
    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => { /* sent to background */ };
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* no longer visible */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* visible again */ };
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* being destroyed */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Key difference**: `OnSleep`/`OnResume` map to the app-level concept, while `Window.Deactivated`/`Window.Resumed` give you per-window granularity (relevant on desktop where multiple windows are possible).

For platform-specific hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.DidEnterBackground(app => { }));
#endif
});
```
